Entering into any &quot;try it and buy it if you like it&quot; arrangement with a
vehicle is a very slippery slope. I know you probably won't like this
answer... but I see only one option:

If your friend is going to drive your car for a month or two, she needs to
buy, register and insure the car in her name. A true arms-length sale is
your only guarantee that you won't be liable for tens of thousands of
dollars of damages if an unforeseen accident turns your good deed into a
nightmare.

Your friend must already like your car or she wouldn't even consider buying
it. Why not sell it to her and transfer it over to her, but offer to buy it
back if she doesn't want to keep it, (less the expenses incurred by you in
the original and subsequent transfers)? If you make her such an offer,
she'll need to trust that you'll honor it. If she won't show you that degree
of trust, I wouldn't find her worthy of your trust.

Take it from someone who loaned his sweetie enough money to buy a new car...
and then had to wait thirteen YEARS for her to completely pay it back,
despite a  written 36-month-loan agreement. Let your friend pay for the car,
etc. and get the complete transaction in writing. There is far too much at
risk for you to shoulder it all.

PL

